    <h1 class="post-title">exploring fluxor: redux-style state in blazor</h1>

    <div class="post-body">
        <p>
            My background is WPF. Specifically, years of building Revit add-ins — the kind of desktop
            tooling that lives inside an existing host application and has to coexist with its event
            model. In that world, MVVM isn't a pattern you choose; it's just how things are done.
            You get <code>INotifyPropertyChanged</code>, <code>RelayCommand</code>, a view model per
            view, and a clean two-way data binding story. It works well and the mental model is
            straightforward: the view model owns the state, the view reflects it, user actions call
            commands.
        </p>
        <p>
            Moving into Blazor, that instinct carries over. Blazor components have lifecycle hooks,
            cascading parameters, and <code>EventCallback</code> — it maps reasonably onto the MVVM
            pattern if you squint. But as components multiply and state starts crossing component
            boundaries, the cracks show up fast. Prop-drilling gets tedious, shared services become
            informal global singletons, and the question of "who owns this state" gets murky.
        </p>
        <p>
            That's what pushed me toward <a href="https://github.com/mrpmorris/Fluxor" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fluxor</a> —
            a Redux/Flux-inspired state management library for Blazor. The pitch is familiar if you've
            spent any time in the frontend ecosystem: a single store, immutable state, state changes
            driven exclusively by dispatched actions, side effects handled by effects. Everything flows
            one direction.
        </p>

        <h2>why not just stick with services?</h2>
        <p>
            The honest answer is: you probably can, for a while. A scoped <code>AppState</code> service
            with a <code>StateChanged</code> event will get you surprisingly far. But the pattern breaks
            down when you need to reason about sequences of state changes, when multiple parts of the UI
            need to react to the same event, or when you want a history of what happened and why. That's
            where a unidirectional architecture earns its complexity cost.
        </p>
        <p>
            Coming from MVVM, the adjustment isn't so much the concept of separated concerns — that's
            familiar — it's the inversion of control. In MVVM, the view model is active: it holds state
            and exposes commands that directly mutate it. In Flux, components are passive dispatchers.
            They fire an action and let the store decide what to do with it. The component has no
            direct handle on the outcome.
        </p>

        <h2>the building blocks</h2>
        <p>
            Fluxor's model maps cleanly onto the Redux primitives. A <strong>feature</strong> defines
            a slice of state with an initial value. A <strong>reducer</strong> is a pure function that
            takes the current state and an action and returns the new state. An <strong>effect</strong>
            handles async work — API calls, navigation, logging — and can dispatch follow-up actions
            when it's done. Components subscribe to state via <code>IState&lt;T&gt;</code> and dispatch
            via <code>IDispatcher</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
            The wiring is mostly attribute-driven, which fits the Blazor style. Reducers are static
            methods decorated with <code>[ReducerMethod]</code>, effects are methods decorated with
            <code>[EffectMethod]</code>, and features are classes that implement
            <code>Feature&lt;TState&gt;</code>. Registration is a single
            <code>AddFluxor</code> call in <code>Program.cs</code> with an assembly scan.
        </p>
        <h2>the tutorial gap</h2>
        <p>
            After working through the introductory material, the most obvious thing is that all the
            examples are small. A counter. A to-do list. A weather fetch with a loading spinner. These
            are fine for learning the mechanics, but they don't stress the pattern in any meaningful way.
            A single feature slice, three actions, and one reducer isn't going to reveal anything about
            how the architecture holds up.
        </p>
        <p>
            The questions I actually have aren't answered by any of it yet. How do you organize features
            when there are dozens of them? How do reducers stay manageable when a single action needs to
            touch multiple state slices? Where does cross-feature coordination live — does one feature
            listen to another's actions, or do you introduce some higher-level orchestration layer? What
            does the action namespace look like when the app grows and similar actions start appearing in
            different contexts?
        </p>
        <p>
            These are the same kinds of questions that don't surface in MVVM tutorials either — you only
            run into them once a project has enough surface area to create real friction. The difference
            is that I've hit those walls in MVVM and know the shape of them. With Fluxor, I'm still
            in the phase where everything looks clean because nothing is complicated yet. That's the
            part I want to push on.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>
